# nftgeo rule set.
#
# One rule per line:  <action> <dir> <proto> <port> <target>
#   action : allow | deny
#   dir    : in      (incoming to this host, matches the source address)
#            out     (outgoing from this host, matches the destination address)
#            fwd-in  (routed/forwarded, matches the source address)
#            fwd-out (routed/forwarded, matches the destination address)
#   proto  : tcp | udp | sctp | all   (port-based; all = tcp and udp)
#            icmp | icmpv6 | esp | ah | gre   (no port; use "-" in the port field)
#            any   (every protocol and port; use "-" in the port field)
#   port   : single port (22), range (5060-5070), list (80,443), or a
#            SERVICE_<NAME> from config (e.g. web); "-" for port-less protocols
#   target : what to match the address against - any mix of, comma-separated:
#              country code (pl), region name (europe),
#              literal IPv4/IPv6 address (203.0.113.5, 2001:db8::1),
#              IPv4/IPv6 with mask (10.0.0.0/8, 2001:db8::/32),
#              a named GROUP_<NAME> from config (used as its lowercase
#                name, e.g. office),
#            or one of the reserved words:
#              any   - every address
#              abuse - the AbuseIPDB blacklist (only with "deny"; needs an
#                      ABUSEIPDB_API_KEY in config to be non-empty)
#
# Every generated rule carries a counter, so "nft list table inet nftgeo"
# shows per-rule packet and byte totals.
#
# How it behaves:
#   - A port that appears in any "allow" rule (for that direction) becomes
#     closed by default: only the listed targets get through, the rest dropped.
#   - A port/direction you never mention is left untouched.
#   - "deny" drops a target without closing the port for everyone else, and is
#     evaluated before "allow".
#   - Replies are always allowed: each chain accepts established/related first,
#     so inbound is permitted only as a response to a request unless an
#     "allow in" rule opens the port for new connections. To allow a service
#     outbound and let its replies back in, write only an "allow out" rule.
#   - The whitelist (config) applies on top, on every managed port.
#   - The AbuseIPDB blacklist is opt-in: it only drops where you write a
#     "deny ... abuse" rule, so you choose the exact direction, protocol, and
#     port(s) it covers - or "deny <dir> any - abuse" to block everything.
#     The drops are evaluated before any "allow", and after the whitelist (so
#     whitelisted addresses are never caught by it). Each abuse rule carries a
#     counter like any other.
#
# Regions are defined in config via REGION_<NAME> variables. Built-in:
# europe, north_america, caribbean, south_america, middle_east, asia, africa,
# oceania. Add your own freely.

# Example: allow inbound SSH from Europe only. Commented out by default so a
# fresh install never locks anyone out - uncomment and adapt before applying.
# WARNING: uncommenting this closes port 22 to every source outside Europe,
# including your own admin host if it is elsewhere. Add your admin IP to
# WHITELIST in config first - the whitelist is checked before this rule and
# prevents a lockout.
# allow in tcp 22 europe

# Examples - uncomment and adapt:
# allow in      all 5060-5070 de       # SIP (tcp+udp) port range, only from Germany
# allow in      tcp 5061      us        # SIPS reachable only from the US
# allow in      tcp 443       any       # HTTPS open to the world (still abuse-filtered)
# allow in      tcp web       any       # named ports via SERVICE_WEB="80 443"
# deny  in      tcp 5060      ru,cn     # block Russia and China on inbound 5060
# allow out     tcp 443       europe,us # only allow outbound HTTPS to Europe and US
# allow out     udp 53        any       # allow outbound DNS anywhere
# allow fwd-in  tcp 443       europe    # gateway: forward inbound 443 only from Europe
# allow fwd-out tcp 80        any       # gateway: let the LAN browse out on port 80
# allow in      icmp -        any       # allow IPv4 ping from anywhere
# allow in      icmpv6 -      any       # allow IPv6 ping/ND from anywhere
# allow fwd-in  esp  -        europe    # IPsec/VPN: forward ESP only from Europe
# allow fwd-in  ah   -        europe    # IPsec/VPN: forward AH only from Europe
# allow in      tcp 22        203.0.113.5        # SSH from one admin IP
# allow in      tcp 22        10.0.0.0/8         # SSH from an internal subnet
# allow in      tcp 443       2001:db8::/32      # HTTPS from an IPv6 prefix
# allow in      tcp 80        198.51.100.0/24,de # mix a subnet with a country
# deny  in      tcp 22        192.0.2.7          # block one bad IP on SSH
# allow in      tcp 22        office             # a GROUP_OFFICE list from the config
# allow in      tcp 443       office,europe      # mix a group with a region
#
# AbuseIPDB blacklist (needs ABUSEIPDB_API_KEY in config):
# deny  in      any -         abuse     # block all inbound traffic from abuse IPs
# deny  in      tcp 22        abuse     # block abuse IPs only on inbound SSH
# deny  in      all 1-65535   abuse     # block abuse IPs on every tcp+udp port in
# deny  out     tcp 443       abuse     # block outbound HTTPS to abuse IPs
# deny  fwd-in  any -         abuse     # gateway: drop forwarded traffic from abuse IPs
